column162: Introduction to Bioinformatics and Genomics in Department of BiologyIntroduction to the representation and analysis of biological sequence and structural information. Description and use of nucleic acid, protein, structure, sequence motif, genome, literture, and other relevant databases. Overview and discussion of basic sequence manipulations and analyses including sequence assembly and editing, restriction and protease analysis, coding region identification, gene prediction, database searching and simiarity analysis, pairwise and multiple sequence alignment, PCR primer design, phylogenetic analyses, protein structure and property prediction, RNA structure prediction, microarray analyses, etc. Laboratory includes demonstrations and practical exercises ilustrating the analyses and concepts presented and discussed in lecture.

column6: First of all, I need to modify my answer from the following page; I DO NOT teach Bioinformatics and DO NOT plan in including it as it does not fit in well the core content of an introductory organismal biology course (diversity of life, ecology, and evoluion) course.  Furthermore, while I feel bioinformatics should be introduced in some meaningful way in the undergraduate education.  It might not be appropriate to teach it in the 1 year introductory biology major series because there is already a great may things to teach and we need to constantly remind our selves to focus on the fundamentals of the discipline.  It is this need to focus on the fundamentals in light of all the things that we may feel students "just have to learn"  (i.e., all the material hat we are tempted to try and squeeze into a course to its ultimate detriment) that prevents me from including bioinformatics.
column105: I feel the whole line of questioning is off track.  There are many different areas of biology students can choose to pursue. column162: BNFO 135. Programming for Bioinformatics. 3 credits, 3 contact hours (3;0;0).The ability to use existing programs and to write small programs to access bioinformatics information or to combine and manipulate various existing bioinformatics programs has ecome a valuable part of the skill set of anyone working with biomolecular or genetic data. This course provides an unerstanding of the architecture of bioinformatics toolkits and experience in writing small bioinformatics programs using one or more of th scripting ("glue") languages frequently employed for such tasks.BNFO 236. Programming For Bioinfo II. 3 credits, 3 contact hours (3;0;0). Python programs for sequence alignment, BLAST, and distance based phylogeny reconstructionBNFO 330. Sequenceanalysis bioinformatics. 3 credits, 3 contact hours (3;0;0): Sequence alignment, hidden Markov models, multiple sequence alignment, expected accuracy alignment, genome and short read alignment, cross-validation, substitution matrices, Perl BNFO 340. Dta analysis for bioinformatics. 3 credits, 3 contact hours (3;0;0).Prerequisites: BNFO 240 and R120 101 or equivalent or permission of instructor. Phylogey reconstruction, local search, and machine learning applications to bioinformatics problems.

column162: All courses are in the biology department.1. Introduction to Bioinformatics: Entry level course for any life sciences student. Students learn basic Python and Linux, and are introduced to common databases. Students are also exposed to many different fieds within the Life Sciences in which a bioinformatics skill set is helpful.2. Computational Biology: Covers major algorithms in bioinformatics. Students are expected to take five computer science classes before this course and are typically strong progrmmers. They code 20-30 different algorithms and learn the strengths/weaknesses of each, and finally they are asked to solve biological questions using their algorithms.3. Bioinformatics: Capstone course for bioinformatics majors. Students are given dataat the start of the semester and asked to test some hypothesis using computational tools they develop, or download. The questions they are expected to address typically have not been solved, so these tend to be real projects and from time-to-time lead to ublications.
column163: Having people with extensive experience in dual disciplines. Many programs focus too heavily on the computers and miss the biology, while others focus too much on data analysis and don't learn coding. I think we find a good balance in our program, but thee aren't many like ours, and their need to be.

column162: MBIO/PBIO 3673 Practical Bioinformatics, Microbiology and Plant BIologyBioinformatics is a rapidly growing field that sits at the crossroads of biology, computer science, and statistics. In its simplest form, bioinformatics represents the use of computes to analyze and interpret various types of biological data. Bioinformatic skills are now indispensable for biologists and this course will introduce undergraduate students to the types of analyses biologists regularly perform at their computers. We will over topics such as accessing genomics databases, aligning DNA and protein sequences, searching genomic databases for similar sequences, analyzing protein structure, and building molecular phylogenies.At the end of this course you will have confidence i your ability to join a research laboratory and use your newly acquired skills to begin exploring the mountains of publicly available biological data. When that future hypothetical boss _hands_ you that gene and wants you to investigate its function, ou should be able to readily use available bioinformatics tools to explore the likely functions of this gene and generate a series of reasonable starting hypotheses.

column162: Bioinformatic Analysis of Macromolecules (BIOL 325), School of Life SciencesThis course will introduce you to the computational analysis of genetic sequences.  Emphasis will be placed on genetic information derived from the human genome project but findngs from the genomes of other model systems will be presented as well.  Each week we will meet for Lectures will discuss available computational tools for extracting biological information from nucleotide and protein sequences.  The computer-based laboratry will employ bioinformatics software to demonstrate how to manage, search and analyze genetic sequences.  Laboratory sessions will include the use of programs to predict genes, perform multiple sequence alignments and analyses, predict protein secondarystructures, construct phylogenetic trees and access publically available databases.  Genomics (BIOL 340) School of Life Scienceshis course introduces students to the analysis of complex genomes. Emphasis is placed on genetic information derived from te human genome project but advances with genomes of other model systems will be discussed. Lectures cover scientific techniques used to map and sequence the human genome, as well as strategies for identification of disease susceptibility genes. The laboraory utilizes an automated DNA sequencer to demonstrate the acquisition of genetic sequences. Laboratory sessions emphasize cycle sequencing of cloned DNA fragments using an automated fluorescent DNA sequencer.Ethics in Bioinformatics (BIOL 425/625) Schol of Life SciencesThis semester we will review a number of topics related to ethics in bioinformatics and in our contemporary society where information is easily shared, stolen and revised.  Your instructor will introduce each topic and lead an introducory discussion.  You will follow up with presentations relevant to the weekly topic. column162: Microbial physiology 424 (BIO/MCRO): in the lab we use bioinformatics tools to localize a transposon in the genome of random transposon mutants. They test these hypotheses with  physiological assays.   Molecular Biology 475 (BIO): We isolate total RNA from yeast, then perform RT-PCR to amplify act1.  We ligate the gee to TOPO vector and transform E coli.  Students use the Yeast Genome Database and DNA strider to create in silico ligations and predict restriction patterns depending on insert orientation. Students then perform the digests.

column162: All courses are offered in the Biology Department.BIOL131: Introduction to Computational Biology: Full course for one semester (lecture-laboratory). This course provides an integrated survey of fundamental questions in molecular biology and the computtional tools that are used to solve them. Elements of molecular biology and computer programming are presented in parallel throughout the semester. Topics include molecular sequence analysis (identifying repeats, regulatory/binding motifs, and genetic varation) using pattern-matching operations on text strings. Assignments will include writing Python programs to analyze human DNA, RNA, and protein sequences. Prerequisite: Biology 101 or consent of the instructor. BIOL331: Computational Systems Biology Full course for one semester (lecture-laboratory).  A survey of network models used to gain a systems-level understanding of biological processes.  Topics include computational models of gene regulation, signal transduction pathways, protein-protein inteactions, and metabolic pathways. Laboratory exercises will involve building a collection of biological networks from public data, implementing a graph library and foundational algorithms, and interpreting computational results. A programming-based indepenent project will answer biological questions by applying graph algorithms to experimental data.  BIOL431: Seminar Biology: Computational Cancer Biology.  Half course for one semester.  Investigation of computational methods to analyze high-throughput iological measurements collected from hundreds to thousands of cancer samples. Biological topics include tumor classification, tumor heterogeneity, and dysregulated signaling pathways. Computational topics include algorithms and models to synthesize, interate, and manage large-scale cancer datasets.

column162: BINF 1101 Intro to BioinformaticsBioinformatics employs mathematical, statistical and computational methods to process large amounts of biologically derived information. This course will introduce the major sub-disciplines and technologies of bioinformaics such as genomics, proteomics, comparative genomics, structural genomics, phylogenomics, large-scale ecological and evolutionary studies and DNA microarrays.BINF 3322 BiostatisticsAn introduction to statistical methods and their application to bilogy. Topics include multiple regression, 2-way ANOVA, non-parametric tests, experimental design, Markov chains and Hidden Markov models. Biological examples will be emphasized throughout. Same as MATH 3322. Prerequisites: MATH 3320, BIOL 1307, BIOL 1107,BIOL 1308 and BIOL 1108. Spring, offered on sufficient demand. BINF 3325 Biological ProgrammingTaught in the context of biological research, this course introduces students to the principles and tools necessary to manipulate and analyze biological dta. With an emphasis on data acquisition and analysis, topics may include computational techniques used in the study of genomes and proteomes, ecological data analysis and mathematical modeling of biological systems. Prerequisite: BIOL 2334 or COSC 2325. pring.BINF 3338 Numerical and Scientific MethodsA survey of standard techniques used to solve numerical and other science-based problems. Topics include roots of equations, systems of linear equations, curve fitting, numerical integration and differntiation, error analysis, number representation, and data visualization. Problems will be solved using programs written in appropriate languages and operating systems. Same as COSC 3338, MATH 3338 and PHYS 3338. Prerequisites: MATH 2314, COSC 1123 and COS 1323. Offered on sufficient demand. BINF 3411 Genomics, ProteomicsAn introductory course whose purpose is to provide a basic understanding of the science of genomics (i.e., the study of genome data). A

column162: Molecular Evolution (BIOL 360) taught in the Department of Biology.  The course is an introduction to the theory and practice of molecular evolution, including an introduction to neutral theory and expectations for how natural selection works on sequences molecular clocks, genetic distances and distance trees, phylogeny and estimation of phylogenies (mostly maximum likelihood). The class is based around problem sets and projects to provide students with opportunities to apply the concepts. The course onsiders only genetic variation among species (divergence), as I teach another course in population genetics that covers topics related to within species genetic variation (polymorphism).
column163: The priority of quantitative literacy - biology is traditionally considered a qualitative science. Pre-clinical training, the driver of a lot of undergraduate curriculum, is primary qualitative. However, many areas of modern biology are actually deeply quntitative and require preparation in math, statistics, and computer science. At my institution the number of students interested in basic quantitative science or planning for careers in science is very small. Therefore, there is little incentive to recognze teaching in this area or to expand course offerings.A consequence is that our doctoral students also have few opportunities to receive practice and development as teachers of these subjects, since we do not have teaching assistant opportunities in he small bioinformatics-content classes.

column162: Willing to share any course materials: email kmetzger@umn.eduCourse: MATH2161: Bioinformatics and BiostatisticsDepartment: Center for Learning InnovationMajor: Bachelor of Science in Health SciencesInstitution: University of Minnesota RochesterCoure Description: Brief introduction to quantitative problem solving using bioinformatics and biostatistics approaches. Student will use authentic data sets and tools to explore questions, analyze data and interpret results. In bioinformatics investigation, students will learn how to obtain and manipulate sequence information from public sources (e.g NCBI Gene database); gain familiarity with database sequence identifiers and conducting database searches; compile sequences and perform sequence alignment; pactice basic phylogenetic analysis and interpretation.Biostatistics skills addressed in the course include exposure to clinical trial and/or experiment design; nonparametric analysis; analysis of variance (ANOVA); logistic regression; survival analysis.

column162: Bioinformatics for Life Sciences, CMB 351, Cell and Molecular Biology.The course covers 1) the use of public bioinformatics databases, such as NCBI, UniProt, UniGene, etc., 2) the use of BLAST algorithms, 3) the use and algorithms of pairwise and multipl sequence alignment; 4) phylogenetic analysis; 5) motif identification; 6) co-evolution; 7) elements of genome analysis.Computational Biology, CMB 452, Cell and Molecular Biology. The course covers: 1) structure and folding of proteins; 2) protein strucure prediction; 3) computer simulations of proteins and nucleic acids; 4) ligand docking simulations and drug design.The department currently prepares an additional course CMB 460 - Genomics, focusing specifically on genome analysis. This new course - aong with the two above - will form a basis for an undergraduate Bioinformatics and Genomics certificate. I hope the certificate will be approved and offered within the next two years.
column163: Life science majors tend to have little to no background in statistics and programming - and a good deal of fear of both. The goal of my current CMB 351 is simply to teach the students how to use the available data and online tools correctly, and how to iterpret the results critically - along with some low-level information on algorithms involved. I would like to teach a senior level course that is project based and involves programing. However, enrollment issues would have to be overcome as well as studets would have to take a Comp. Sci. programing course as a prerequisite. In other words, for a cell and molecular biology major with huge emphasis on wet lab proficiency, adding 2-4 computational courses to the required curriculum is not palatable. The bes target group is CMB-major/CompSci-minor, but there are currently few such students, at least in my institution.

column162: Molecular Phylogenetics Workshop based introduction to comparative evolutionary techniques using molecular sequences. Students will learn to produce robust molecular phylogenies, edit and align genetic sequences, select and apply best-fit models of moleular evolution, carry out phylogenetic analyses, interpret phylogenetic tree topologies, and determine timing of divergence using fossil calibrated phylogenies.After completion of this course students will be able to edit and align Sanger sequence dat, perform Bayesian and maximum likelihood analyses using appropriate models of nucleotide substitution, understand how to interpret tree topologies and nodal support, be able to produce time-calibrated molecular phylogenies, understand the problems in delmitating species, be able to recognize cryptic species, and have a basic understanding of next generation sequencing using both Roche 454 and Ilumina Hi-Seq platforms. Students will also look at how to optimize morphological characters onto molecular tree, which can be used to test hypotheses about evolution.

column237: I am not against adding aspects of bioinformatics to course curriculum. However, I think much thought needs to be put into adding/creating dedicated bioinformatics curriculum. Bioinformatics is still a rapidly developing field. It relies on the newest tecniques and knowledge in genetics, computer science, and statistics. Unfortunately my experience with dedicated bioinformatics curriculum has been that the bioinformatics courses are taught as a hodgepodge, containing many different disciplines that studens are never able to fully master. Many of the students I have worked with walk away feeling as though they are more aware of bioinformatics, but have not mastered any part of it. I feel that many students would be better served by completing a degree in cmputer science with a masters in biology, or vice versa. However, with a rigorous curriculum combining genetics, computer science, and statistics, I do believe it would be possible to create a core bioinformatics program.

column58: There is some resistance from experimental biologists to include algorithmic aspects of bioinformatics. As a consequence, most bioinformatics modules end up focusing on various tools alone. I strongly feel that students should have at least a rudimentary nderstanding of the algorithms driving bioinformatics tools. There lies another challenge: not many experimental biologists have a good understanding of the algorithms.
column162: Research Approaches in Molecular Genetics (Science and Technology Honors Program) - I offer a course-based undergraduate research experience to freshman students through this course. This laboratory course introduces students to the world of genome enginering using the CRISPR-Cas9 system.  The course participants will design and construct CRISPR guide RNA to target specific gene sequences in the zebrafish genome.  The final outcome of the laboratory exercises is to create a set of validated CRISPR RNA, whch can efficiently target zebrafish genes and cause mutations.  Learning molecular genetics in the context of genome engineering is an exciting opportunity! This is an intensive, inquiry-based laboratory course focusing on the fundamental methods of recmbinant DNA technology. Students will work in teams of three on a self-contained research project involving reading published literature, making a hypothesis and posing a biological question, search and analysis of biological databases; DNA and RNA; polymrase chain reaction; plasmid cloning; DNA sequencing; phenotype analysis and genotyping.Course Objectives:This is an inquiry-based laboratory course with three main objectives:Enable students to develop a strong understanding of practical and theoreical aspects of experimental methods and techniques; understand the applicability and limitations of these methods and techniques in research investigations.Enable students to learn how to design scientific experiments and how to critically evaluate the esulting data.Enable students to communicate their research in different contexts.

column162: Biopsychology Lab, Psychology Department, UCLAWhen the Bioinformatics module is offered (which is not every quarter), students quantify a brain phenotype in recombinant inbred mouse strains, control for uncontrolled variables via a regression analysis, nd do a QTL analysis via the Mouse Brain Library (http://www.mbl.org/) and GeneNetwork (http://www.genenetwork.org/webqtl/main.py). Then students find a gene in the chromosomal ROI that is highly expressed in that region of the brain via UCSC Genome Browsr (http://genome.ucsc.edu/), find out what specific cells in that given brain region highly express this gene via the Allen Brain Atlas (http://www.brain-map.org/), find out the sequence of the gene via Entrez gene, and find relevant articles on this genevia pubmed.

column162: Biol-4790 Biometry - 4 crd hrs - Three hours of lecture, plus a 2.5 hour lab. The course covers basic probability, descriptive and inferential statistics, and statistical modeling. We also cover principles of experimental design, hypothesis testing, philoophy of science, and professional ethics.  In the lab students will learn data structures, data manipulation, and how to perform and interpret statistical analysis. All labs are done in the R computational environment. Biol-4670 Population Biology - 3 cd hrs - Students learn the theoretical principles of how biological populations grow and change over time. How biotic and abiotic forces regulate and influence population sizes and distributions.  Student also learn how to model populations, interactions,and distribution in the R computational environment.  They also learn how to test  hypotheses via computational methods.

column105: Some of my students have troubles with basic computer skills and concepts such as:  knowing if a file is on their computer or in Google Docs, capturing and editing images, searching for a word on a web page, constructing effective Google searches, troublehooting computer problems.  The databases we use most often aren't listed above.  These include PubChem, the PDB, the NCBI structure database, dbSNP, PubMed, PubMed Central, OMIM, ClinVar, the NCBI Gene database, the taxonomy database, and the EOL.  As fa as tools, we use blastn, blastp, blastx, Cobalt for multiple alignments, and the phylogenetic tree tool at the NCBI.  A skill we also stress is reading genetic maps since many students have a hard time with this.Excel and tools for graphing should be mntioned also.  True, professional bioinformaticists would scoff at Excel, but it's a really helpful tool for teaching students about visualizing data, using a variety of graphs, concepts like rows and columns, importing and manipulating data, CSV formats,pivot tables, etc.

column162: BITC 2350 Bioinformatics, Biotechnology, This course serves as an introduction to bioinformatics with an emphasis on tools students are likely to use as biotechnicians.  Students work with tools for analyzing sequences, structures, and function.
column163: Reading level of the students:  scientific papers and information are written at a higher reading level than many college students can understand. Lack of access to literature:  community college students don't have access to scientific papers unless thy're in PubMed Central.  So, even when we push to have them read papers, it's not easy to get them the articles.Diversity of platforms and operating systems:  I used to do a lot with Excel and pivot tables but I gave up since there were too many types o Excel for me to install on my computer.Poor backgrounds in chemistry:  it's hard for students to understand amino acids if they don't understand chemistry concepts like covalent bonds, ionic interactions, etc.I think many of the people who teach undegraduate biology are not very familiar with using many different bioinformatics tools and so they're not aware of the many tools available or how a combination of those tools can be used to approach researching a problem.

column163: - Despite unprecedented access to computers, students are increasingly computer-illiterate. Very few have ever programmed in any way (even a script or macro), used the command line or gone beyond the very basic features of off-the-shelf software. They almst need a course to teach them to use computers before they are ready to think about programming.- Bioinformatics software is diverse and changes fast; there are few standards and limited documentation. Working scientists use whatever rather random collction of software they've found useful in their particular areas. So, it's hard to define a core set of skills that students "should" know across the board, and very hard to have "how to use this software" exercises that will still be useful in a year.-Faculty are constantly re-inventing the wheel at their various institutions; there are few good and well-known resources where hands-on bioinformatics exercises are available and documented.

column162: Analysis of Algorithms, Computer ScienceThis course provides a comprehensive introduction to computer algorithms. The emphasis is on the design of efficient algorithms and data structures, proofs of their correctness, and analysis of their complexity. Anumber of algorithmic concepts and techniques are covered, including recursion, incremental design, divide-and-conquer, greedy algorithms, amortized analysis, and dynamic programming. The algorithms studied include sorting, searching, breadth-first search depth-first search, minimum spanning trees, shortest paths, network flow, and string matching. Data structures studied include hash tables, heaps, binary search trees, and red-black trees. This course is meant as a follow-up to a course in data structure. Knowledge of elementary data structures such as stacks, queues, and linked lists are assumed. In addition, a module will be given on algorithms relevant to bioinformatics, which studies molecular sequence data (DNA, RNA, and protein). Much of the materil learned in this course, such as graphs, trees, dynamic programming, and search algorithms apply to this new discipline.

column162: BIO 380: Practical Computing for ScientistsThis course will focus on developing the base tool set for implementing advanced computing in the design and analysis research projects. Content of the course is geared towards novice students (i.e. those with lttle or no previous programming experience) who will learn practical computational approaches to modern research questions by applying programming concepts and approaches to real data sets. Areas of study will focus on skills related to data manipulation,management, and analysis. BIO 410: BioinformaticsEmphasizes modern genomics focused on basic and applied questions involving human genome biology and genomics for drug development and agricultural application. Students will learn to conduct bioinformatc analysis using data from genomic research projects of different species.BIO 412: Comparative GenomicsThis course will explore the area of genomics and its relationship to both basic and applied areas of research. Students will learn about the applicaions and contributions of a "genomic" perspective to topics such as evolutionary biology, functional genetics, genetic structure, and systems biology.

column58: The courses would likely be low-enrollment and we are always under a budget crunch.  There is nearly zero chance that such a course would become required in the near future.
column107: We do not have computers in our wet labs, so building in bioinformatics activities requires reserving computer labs, which can be difficult and prevents us from combining wet lab activities with computational activities.There is NO support for Linux O at my institution, and in fact seems to be actively against this OS.  Only Windows and Mac can be used.  We do not have any computer clusters that I'm aware of and only have marginally powerful desktops, so processing and performance might be an issue (amittedly, not much of one in short teaching exercises).
column163: Lack of space in the curriculum.  We cannot add anymore courses, and existing courses already have high content loads, so it's a challenge to build in new (or very different) content.Lack of computational skills among students.  Despite repeated refernce to current students being "digital natives", most students have no functional knowledge of computers or programs beyond their handful of favorite apps on their phone.  It's a constant source of surprise given how ubiquitous computers are in their live.  For example, many students have no idea what the difference is between "the internet", "an internet browser", "a server", and other commonly used terms.  When the one thing they know how to do fails, many students have no idea how to work around it (e.., trying a different browser if an assigned activity doesn't work in their usual one).  I know that the students are capable of a lot, but the lack of experience and interest in anything computational is a large hurdle.  Many bioinformatics procedure are very button-click activities that allow students to follow directions without deeply thinking about material.  This is the part that I struggle with most in developing activities, because I want them to connect to the concepts we're covering and not ust blindly report direct results (e.g., reporting an E-value without giving any thought to what that means biologically).

For the project portion of the course, all students will utilize public genomic databases and software to contribute to a multi-institute on-going analysis and annotation of understudied regons of the Drosophila genome.  This project work makes students eligible for future co-author status on emerging publications by the Genomics Education Partnership consortium.

column5: 1_Dedicated course for life-science majors
column162: Fundamentals of Bioinformatics - Biology - In this course students are introduced to the fundamental concepts behind major branches of bioinformatics, from the study of DNA sequences to the study of macromolecular structure, to the detection of differentil gene activity. Students perform hands-on analyses using publicly available data and toolsBioinformatics in Medicine and Biology - In this course students learn about R and statistics and for their final project they analyze a publicly available datafrom start to end. They start with downloading and normalizing data, identifying differentially expressed genes, clustering and then finally Gene Ontology over-representation analysisProgramming for Biologists - Students learn how to write software prgrams in Python in order to analyze Next-generation sequencing dataBiological Databases and Datamining - Students learn about different types of Biological data and how to store and query them in relational databases such as MySQL and SQLite. They als learn how to use data-mining methods such as Decision Trees, Logistic Regression, and Clustering to analyze publicly available dataApplied Genomics - Analysis of Next-generation sequencing data using High Performance Computing (HPC) systems and R. Soe topics include RNA-seq, CHIP-seq, and SNP analysis
column163: Students need a fundamental understanding of Statistics and also have to be comfortable writing some basic code in programming languages such as R and Python. This is a big change for traditional biology but data analysis has become an important part of uderstanding biology.

Flow of genetic information. Determining structure and function of gnes. Mutation and DNA repair systems. Genetic basis of disease, DNA technology. With lab.2. BI308 Molecular Biology II: Genomics and epigenomics. Components and architecture of genomes. Linkage, physical mapping, and DNA sequencing. Comparing genomes of ifferent species. Role of gene expression and gene networks in differentiation and morphogenesis. Role of DNA methylation and chromatin remodeling in regulation of genes. Role of regulatory RNAs in gene expression. With lab.3. BI311: Biostatistics. Lectue course devoted to rigorous grounding in biological statistics, and in the application of statistical models to global health problems. Biostatistics is a lecture and hands-on course designed to provide students with the opportunity to develop statistica reasoning skills appropriate to analyze and implement biological experiments. Exemplars and case studies will be primarily derived from the public health field. Topics include principles of experimental design, sampling and variables, data categories andassumptions of parametric statistics, risk analysis, repeated measures, goodness of fit and contingency table analyses, and the general linear model.BI420: Systems biology. This course will focus on the frontiers of our understanding of the multi-level ntworks that underlie biological systems. Lecture course reviewing the key concepts of the systems biology approach to ecological, organismal and cellular systems. Contribution of cornerstone technologies such as genomics, bioinformatics, proteomics and meabolomics will be reviewed, along with their computational foundations.

column162: BioinformaticsGenetics & Biochemistry Dept.Bioinformatics is a dynamic scientific discipline that utilizes computational and statistical methods for solving biological problems.  A major theme in bioinformatics is to integrate and understand biologica data generated by genome sequencing projects and other high-throughput molecular biology efforts. Bioinformatics tools are developed to reveal fundamental mechanisms underlying the structure and function of macromolecules, biochemical pathways, disease pocesses, and genome evolution  Although many bioinformatics problems are solved by computation and programming, this course itself does not require (practical) computer programming. However, it is expected that all of the students learn how to use the avalable bioinformatics software to solve biological problems. The aim is to emphasize critical thinking: understanding how these tools work in principle and developing a computational mind for biological problems. Major topics to be discussed in the course nclude: sequence analysis & algorithms, gene annotation, protein sequence analysis, proteomics, gene expression analysis, comparative genomics, genetic networks and pathways analysis, and systems biology.Biomedical BioinformaticsGenetics & Biochemisry Dept.Bioinformatics is a dynamic scientific discipline that utilizes computational and statistical methods for solving biological problems.  _Translational bioinformatics_ is an emerging discipline that bridges the gap between information stored n databases and application of this information to diagnosis, prognosis, and treatment of disease.  I have named this course Biomedical Bioinformatics because it sounds better!  The topics we will cover are taken from the free _textbook_ and inclue:_	Biomedical Knowledge Integration(Ch.1)_	Data-Driven View of Disease Biology(Ch.2)_	Small Molecules and Disease(Ch.3)_	Protein Interactions and Disease(Ch.4)_	Network Biology Approach
column163: 1.  Established biologists who think that bioinformatics is a separate discipline and not a fundamental part of biological science.  Molecular biology techniques are not treated this way and are often blended in teaching and fundamental to research like boinformatics.  See #3 below.2. Command line/scripting barrier.  Many new students don't understand the computer  other than as a cluster of GUI icons that you slide around to do stuff which makes command lines and filesystems very difficult concepts.3.  Department curriculum committees not seeing that scripting and HPC usage is a fundamental toolkit of biology thus not allotting credit hours to practical training.   For example, qPCR/PCR is a fundamental skill but RNAseq/GBS analysis is not.

column162: Biology 4930 Genes, Genomes, and MetagenomesGenomics is the study of the content, structure, organization, evolution, and conservation of whole genomes.  Because of its reliance on precision instrumentation and scale, and the unprecedented volume of dat produced, genomics is unusual among biological disciplines in its integration of engineering, statistics, and information science.  Genomics also requires the biologist to engage in systems thinking by taking a wide view of the dynamic physical and inforational network that comprises a single genome.  One must further consider the human genome as itself a component of an even larger network of genomes that make up the holobiont_that_s us plus our always-changing resident community of microbial pals. After covering these and other topics, and carrying out a substantial genome annotation project for the lab component of the course, we explore personal genomics, or how all this information and understanding affects our lives as 21st century human beings

column162: Bio 439 - Bioinformatics - biology departmentThis course focuses on practical aspects of biological databases and analyses of molecular data. Students will learn about vast resources that are available, how to access them, and retrieve only the desired iformation. Sequence comparison and alignment methods will be presented. Practical aspects of programming such as BLAST and FASTA will be discussed with class activities pertinent to these search engines as well as different strategies of multiplealignmens will be investigated. They will learn how to analyze protein sequences including secondary structure prediction, protein function prediction (based on motifs and functional domains), and structural modeling. The entire course will be well balanced betwen a theoretical description of computational biology methods and practical aspects of bioinformatics. Upon completion of this course, students will have sufficient knowledge to retrieve desired information from biological databases based on both text and equence data. They will learn what public resources are available in terms of databases and software. They will know how to interpret results in biological context and how to adjust different parameters in the software to obtain exact desired results.

column163: The biggest challenge is institutional inertia.  While people can reasonably disagree about details of course content and pedagogy, we have known for many years now that every student working in life sciences will need much stronger training in bioinformaics and in the relevant mathematical/statistical/computational background than is the standard today.  The main obstacle today to getting this material taught to students is making it an expectation of any institution offering a biology problem that this eeds to be part of the curriculum and that room needs to be cleared and faculty hired to make that happen.  That is an agenda that requires support by undergraduate institutions but also in graduate and medical school admissions, accrediting authorities, nd funders of training grants.

column162: BIO 316: Introduction to Computational Biology, Biology Department Course Description: Broad overview of computational biology/bioinformatics with a significant problem-solving component.  Significant hands-on practice will include using computationaltools to solve a variety of biological problems and an introduction to the Python programming language. Topics may include: database searching, sequence alignment, gene prediction, RNA and protein structure prediction, construction of phylogenetic trees, omparative and functional genomics. Learning Outcomes:  1)	Understand the current scope of bioinformatics research2)	Understand the position and role of computational analyses in the scientific method3)	Become familiar with commonly used biologial databases and software tools4)	Be able to select the appropriate data/tools for your research question5)	Evaluate and accurately interpret results obtained from bioinformatics analyses6)	Use basic programming techniques to access and manipulate squence data7)	Understand the challenges and basic techniques for handling large datasets8)	Actively engage with primary literature that relies on computational/bioinformatics techniques9)	Develop the ability to approach biological problems in a quanitative fashion

column162: BCB stands for 'Bioinformatics and Computational Biology'.  All of our BCB courses are cross-listed with either Biology & Biotechnology (BB), Computer Science (CS), or Mathematical Sciences (MA).  Some are offered as joint senior / grad level classes.CB 100X/BB 100X. EXPLORING BIOINFORMATICS AND COMPUTATIONAL BIOLOGYCat. I.  Life scientists are generating huge amounts of data on many different scales, from DNA and protein sequence, to information on biological systems such as protein interaction netorks, brain circuitry, and ecosystems.  Analyzing these kinds of data requires quantitative knowledge and approaches using computer science and mathematics.  In this project-based course, students will use case studies to learn about both important biologcal problems and the computational tools and algorithms used to study them.  Students will study a sampling of topics in the field, including such areas as complex disease genetics, analysis of a flu epidemic, investigating antibiotic resistance, and undestanding the behavior of swarms, such as schooling fish.  Computational tools explored will include both freely-available web-based tools as well as guided programming using Python.Recommended background: High school biology. Programming experience is nt required.BCB 3010 / BB 3010 SIMULATION IN BIOLOGYCat II. Computer simulations are becoming increasingly important in understanding and predicting the behavior of a wide variety of biological systems, ranging from metastasis of cancer cells, to sprad of disease in an epidemic, to management of natural resources such as fisheries and forests.  In this course, students will learn to use a graphical programming language to simulate biological systems.  Most of the classroom time will be spent working ndividually or in groups, first learning the language, and then programming simulation projects.  We will also discuss several papers on biological simulations from the primary scientific literature.  In cons

column162: The SYBB Survey Series is composed of the following course sequence: (A) Technologies in Bioinformatics, (B) Data Integration in Bioinformatics, (C) Translational Bioinformatics, and (D) Programming for Bioinformatics. Each standalone section of this coure series introduces students to an aspect of a bioinformatics project - from data collection (SYBB 311/411A), to data integration (SYBB 311/411B), to research applications (SYBB 311/411C), with a fourth module (SYBB 311/411D) introducing basic bioinformatcs programming skills.  SYBB 311/411A, SYBB 311/411B, and SYBB 311/411C are offered as a block in the fall. SYBB 311/411D is offered in the spring semester. Each class is graded separately.
